	<h3>Improving the User Interface of a Mall Directory</h3>
	<h4>Course: CPSC 344 - Human-Computer Interaction</h4>
	<h4>Skills: paper prototyping, use of wireframing tools(Balsamiq, FluidUI), conducting observation studies, forming questionnaires and surveys</h4>
	<p>The goal of this project was to improve upon the current interface of an existing system through an iterative design process where we included user feedback at each stage. My team and I felt that current mall directories are inadequate in helping shoppers quickly find store locations in a mall. By conducting questionnaires and interviews with mall shoppers, store managers and customer service representatives, we not only validated the need for an improved interface, but we also identified the problems with the current iteration. These problems included the confusing use of letters and numbers to locate stores on a map, the fact that directories are static and immobile, and the inability to quickly plot the fastest route to a desired store. We settled on creating a mobile application, which allowed us to create functionality that would solve many of the problems that were outlined from our research. At each stage of the process, we developed a prototype and had users evaluate them using a variety of user evaluation techniques, including cognitive walkthroughs and think-aloud observations. The purpose of doing multiple iterations and including users at each stage is to confirm whether our system behaviour matches the user's requirements. Hence, when the product is completed, there would be a greater buy-in and satisfaction among stakeholders. </p>
